you&#39;re not using ngOnInit in a way that I would use it. There are no Inputs so the lifecycle hook isn&#39;t really needed. Plus you&#39;re doing multiple subscribes inside another. I think your dependency here is the router param which kicks off the other two subscribes.

my advice is to assign the this.route.paramMap as a property (componentState$) in your TS and use the async pipe to subscribe to it within your template file via 

    &lt;ng-container *ngIf=&quot;componentState$ | async as state&quot;&gt;&lt;/ng-container&gt;

in your ts, at the time just pipe off the params
  

     componentState$ = this.route.paramMap.pipe(
          map(params =&gt; params.get(&#39;word_id&#39;)), 
          switchMap(wordId =&gt; combineLatest([
             this.oxford.getDefinition(wordId), 
             this.oxford.getSynAndAnt(wordId)
          ]).pipe(
                map(([def, synant]) =&gt; ({ def, synant }))
             )
          )
       );

your template will now have access to all your data in dot notation. Also, this means you only have one subscribe and you don&#39;t need to unsubscribe because your template async pipe will do both for you. No need to assign other props in your ts.

